<h2 class="section-head">Positioning Villa Sarchi <em>for Your Customers</em></h2>

<p class="body">Villa Sarchi gives a roaster a small education to hand to a curious customer. The story is genuinely interesting: a Bourbon plant in Costa Rica mutated into a compact dwarf, the same kind of natural change that produced Caturra and Pacas, and that practical little plant now grows at altitude in Matagalpa producing a bright, clean, sweet cup. That is a two-sentence story a barista can tell, and it positions the coffee as a thoughtful choice rather than a generic single origin.</p>

<p class="body">On the menu, Villa Sarchi pairs naturally with the rest of the El Quetzal lineup. Set it next to the <a href="/microlots/washed-java-green-coffee" style="color: var(--gold); text-decoration: none;">washed Java</a> as the brighter, more acidic counterpoint, and use it to round out a house blend that needs lift. Customers who appreciate the clarity of a good Villa Sarchi are exactly the audience that will reach for the farm's rarer lots when they drop.</p>

